&gt;&gt; Oh, about 150 million years...

00:02:43.640 --> 00:02:44.640
&gt;&gt; Would be a light year.

00:02:44.640 --> 00:02:45.640
&gt;&gt; Would be a light year.

00:02:45.640 --> 00:02:47.330
That is what I believe it would be.

00:02:47.330 --> 00:02:48.330
&gt;&gt; It is a distance.

00:02:48.330 --> 00:02:49.330
&gt;&gt; Is it a distance?

00:02:49.330 --> 00:02:50.330
A light year?

00:02:50.330 --> 00:02:51.330
&gt;&gt; Have you heard the term exoplanet?

00:02:51.330 --> 00:02:52.330
&gt;&gt; No.

00:02:52.330 --> 00:02:53.330
&gt;&gt; No.

00:02:53.330 --> 00:02:54.330
Never.

00:02:54.330 --> 00:02:55.330
&gt;&gt; Exoplanet.

00:02:55.330 --> 00:02:56.330
No.

00:02:56.330 --> 00:02:57.910
&gt;&gt; Like a planet that we are not aware?

00:02:57.910 --> 00:03:01.159
&gt;&gt; Well, exo should be... could be short for
something.

00:03:01.159 --> 00:03:04.030
&gt;&gt; Extraterrestrial planet or extraterrestrial
life, maybe.

00:03:04.030 --> 00:03:05.500
&gt;&gt; Something outside our planet.

00:03:05.500 --> 00:03:10.590
&gt;&gt; So an exoplanet is simply a planet that
orbits a star other than the sun.

00:03:10.590 --> 00:03:15.200
Exo just means external, outside, so outside
our solar system.

00:03:15.200 --> 00:03:16.310
So it is just a planet.

00:03:16.310 --> 00:03:17.760
You know, you can...

00:03:17.760 --> 00:03:19.060
&gt;&gt; How many have you found?&gt;&gt;

00:03:19.060 --> 00:03:20.400
Me personally?

00:03:20.400 --> 00:03:22.730
I have found six.

00:03:22.730 --> 00:03:29.680
But overall we now know of over 800 planets
that have been confirmed and another probably

00:03:29.680 --> 00:03:33.760
2000 planets that are waiting for information,
but are pretty strong candidates.

00:03:33.760 --> 00:03:38.620
So we don’t see the planet directly, we
see its impact on the start that it orbits.

00:03:38.620 --> 00:03:44.850
We do it from the ground with a angle Australian
telescope and we look for the wobble of the

00:03:44.850 --> 00:03:46.280
star as the planet orbits it.

00:03:46.280 --> 00:03:49.580
The planet goes around and the start moves
backwards and forwards.

00:03:49.580 --> 00:03:54.270
So if you can imagine seeing that from sort
of along the line of sight a little bit more,

00:03:54.270 --> 00:04:00.650
say like in this cartoon here, then you would
see the star moving towards you and moving

00:04:00.650 --> 00:04:01.650
away from you.

00:04:01.650 --> 00:04:07.350
And so what we see here is the light from
the star becoming ever so slightly bluer as

00:04:07.350 --> 00:04:11.740
it moves towards us and ever so slightly redder
as it moves away.

00:04:11.740 --> 00:04:16.160
The big problem is that the main kind of planet
you end up finding with this wobble technique,

00:04:16.160 --> 00:04:21.310
because it is really reliant on the mass of
the planet, basically like Jupiter, Saturn

00:04:21.310 --> 00:04:23.830
and then we have started to get down to Neptune
and Uranus.

00:04:23.830 --> 00:04:30.250
&gt;&gt; To find smaller planets NASA launched Kepler,
a one meter telescope with a 95 megapixel

00:04:30.250 --> 00:04:31.250
camera.

00:04:31.250 --> 00:04:36.820
Its mission is to observe 130,000 stars in
our galaxy and look for dips in brightness

00:04:36.820 --> 00:04:39.420
caused by planets passing in front of them.

00:04:39.420 --> 00:04:44.940
&gt;&gt; So Kepler-62 is a solar system with five
planets and the planets are very similar in

00:04:44.940 --> 00:04:49.410
size to the terrestrial planets, the rocky
planets in our own solar system.

00:04:49.410 --> 00:04:52.310
They have a star in the middle and then you
have three inner planets.

00:04:52.310 --> 00:04:56.540
There is a green band which is this habitable
zone, the goldilocks zone where you can expect

00:04:56.540 --> 00:04:59.840
liquid water to exist on the surface of the
planet.

00:04:59.840 --> 00:05:03.550
And, in fact, there are two planets inside
the habitable zone around Kepler-62.

00:05:03.550 --> 00:05:08.420
If you are going to start looking for life
around nearby stars, this is probably the

00:05:08.420 --> 00:05:09.699
best one to start with.

00:05:09.699 --> 00:05:11.960
&gt;&gt; Is there life beyond the earth?&gt;&gt;

00:05:11.960 --> 00:05:13.639
Well we don’t know for sure.

00:05:13.639 --> 00:05:15.990
We can’t say yes definitely.

00:05:15.990 --> 00:05:17.910
But the probability is very high.

00:05:17.910 --> 00:05:19.930
There are at least 200 billion stars in our
galaxy.

00:05:19.930 --> 00:05:24.910
We now know that on average there is at least
one planet per star in our galaxy alone and

00:05:24.910 --> 00:05:28.840
there are another 100 plus billion galaxies
in the universe.

00:05:28.840 --> 00:05:33.480
We also now know, thanks to the Kepler spacecraft,
that at least one in six of those is earth

00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:34.480
sized.

00:05:34.480 --> 00:05:38.139
And so that is 33 billion potential earth
sized planets.

00:05:38.139 --> 00:05:39.920
Not all of them are going to be able to have
life.

00:05:39.920 --> 00:05:42.870
But the probability is getting pretty high
already at this stage.

00:05:42.870 --> 00:05:48.350
&gt;&gt; So there is no definitive evidence that
alien life exists, but the sheer size of the

00:05:48.350 --> 00:05:51.710
numbers suggest that they must be out there
somewhere.

00:05:51.710 --> 00:05:56.030
But with the vast distances across the universe,
chances are it is going to be a long time

00:05:56.030 --> 00:06:00.449
before we know for certain that we are not
alone.

